n array is a special type of object used to store multiple values in a single variable. These values are ordered and indexed starting from 0.

🧠 Key Characteristics
✅ Ordered collection of elements

✅ Can hold any data type: numbers, strings, objects, even other arrays

✅ Zero-based indexing: first element is at index 0

✅ Dynamic: you can add, remove, or modify elements




✅ 1. Using reverse() Method
js
const original = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const reversed = original.reverse();

console.log(reversed); // [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]
⚠️ Note: reverse() modifies the original array.

🔁 2. Without Modifying Original (Using slice())
js
const original = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const reversed = original.slice().reverse();

console.log(reversed); // [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]
console.log(original); // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
🧠 3. Manual Reversal Using a Loop
js
const original = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const reversed = [];

for (let i = original.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
  reversed.push(original[i]);
}

console.log(reversed); // [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]









//////////centre of array //////////


If the array has an odd number of elements, the center is a single element:

js
const arr = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50];
const centerIndex = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
const centerValue = arr[centerIndex];

console.log(centerValue); // 30
